.TH LAZYPAC 1 "2026-05-17" "1.2.0" "Lazy Pacman"

.SH NAME
lazypac \- simple human-readable wrapper for pacman/yay/paru

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B lazypac
.I command
.RI [ package ...]
.RI [ flags ...]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B lazypac
is a thin bash wrapper around
.BR yay (1)
or
.BR paru (1)
(whichever is installed) that maps short, readable subcommands to their
underlying pacman flags.
No databases, no tracking, no hidden logic - every command prints exactly
what it runs underneath.
.PP
At startup,
.B lazypac
detects the AUR helper in order: first
.BR yay ,
then
.BR paru .
If neither is found it exits with an error message.
.PP
Upgrade logs are stored in
.I $XDG_DATA_HOME/lazypac
(defaults to
.IR ~/.local/share/lazypac ).

.SH COMMANDS

.SS Package management

.TP
.BI "install " "pkg [pkg ...]"
Install one or more packages from the official repositories or the AUR.
Runs:
.B $AUR_HELPER -S
.I pkg ...
.IP
.I Example - install a single package:
.RS
.nf
lazypac install firefox
.fi
.RE
.IP
.I Example - install several packages at once without confirmation prompts:
.RS
.nf
lazypac install firefox chromium vlc --noconfirm
.fi
.RE

.TP
.BI "remove " "pkg [pkg ...]"
Remove one or more packages together with any dependencies that would
become orphaned after the removal.
Configuration files in
.I /etc
are left untouched (use
.B purge
to remove them as well).
Runs:
.B $AUR_HELPER -Rs
.I pkg ...
.IP
.I Example - remove a package you no longer use:
.RS
.nf
lazypac remove gimp
.fi
.RE
.IP
.I Example - remove a group of related packages in one command:
.RS
.nf
lazypac remove gimp inkscape krita
.fi
.RE

.TP
.BI "purge " "pkg [pkg ...]"
Like
.B remove
but also deletes configuration files left behind by the package(s) in
.IR /etc .
Runs:
.B $AUR_HELPER -Rns
.I pkg ...
.IP
.I Example - cleanly uninstall a package and wipe its config:
.RS
.nf
lazypac purge openssh
.fi
.RE
.IP
.I Example - purge several packages non-interactively:
.RS
.nf
lazypac purge openssh cups --noconfirm
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B update
Sync the package databases without upgrading anything.
.PP
.B Warning:
running
.B \-Sy
without a subsequent upgrade leaves the system in a partial upgrade state,
which is unsafe on Arch Linux.
Prefer
.B lazypac upgrade
for routine use.
.B update
is provided for cases where you explicitly need a database refresh only.
Runs:
.B $AUR_HELPER -Sy
.IP
.I Example - refresh package databases:
.RS
.nf
lazypac update
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B upgrade
Sync databases and upgrade all installed packages, including AUR packages.
Runs:
.B $AUR_HELPER -Syu
.IP
.I Example - standard full system upgrade:
.RS
.nf
lazypac upgrade
.fi
.RE
.IP
.I Example - also rebuild AUR packages that have updated VCS sources (git, svn, ...):
.RS
.nf
lazypac upgrade --devel
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B safe-upgrade
Like
.B upgrade
but takes a snapshot of all installed package versions before and after the
upgrade, compares them, and writes a human-readable log file to
.IR $LOG_DIR/upgrade_TIMESTAMP.log .
The log lists every package whose version changed (old \(-> new) and every
package that was newly installed.
If nothing changed it records that as well.
.PP
After the upgrade,
.B safe-upgrade
scans
.I /etc
for any
.I .pacnew
or
.I .pacsave
files left behind by pacman and, if found, prints their paths with a reminder
to run
.B sudo pacdiff
to resolve them.
.PP
Temp snapshots in
.I /tmp
are created with
.BR mktemp (1)
(random name, created atomically) and removed on exit via
.BR trap ,
even if interrupted.
Runs:
.B $AUR_HELPER -Syu
followed by snapshot, diff, and pacnew check.
.IP
.I Example - upgrade with a full version diff saved for review later:
.RS
.nf
lazypac safe-upgrade
.fi
.RE
.IP
.I Example - safe upgrade, including VCS rebuilds, without confirmation prompts:
.RS
.nf
lazypac safe-upgrade --devel --noconfirm
.fi
.RE

.SS Updates

.TP
.B check-updates
List all packages that have newer versions available in the repositories,
without downloading or installing anything.
.PP
For each package the current and available version are shown side by side
.RI ( old " -> " new ).
Packages whose first version segment changes (e.g. 1.x to 2.x) are
prefixed with
.B [!]
and printed in bold red when the output is a terminal, indicating a major
version jump that may require manual attention.
.PP
A summary line at the end reports the total number of pending updates and
how many are classified as major.
.PP
When
.BR checkupdates (8)
.RI ( pacman-contrib )
is present it is used to fetch up-to-date results safely.
Otherwise
.B lazypac
falls back to
.B $AUR_HELPER -Qu
using the local sync database; run
.B lazypac update
first if the database may be stale.
Colors are suppressed automatically when stdout is not a terminal.
.IP
.I Example - see what is pending before a full upgrade:
.RS
.nf
lazypac check-updates
.fi
.RE

.SS Query

.TP
.BI "search " "pkg"
Search repositories and the AUR for packages whose name or description
matches
.IR pkg .
Runs:
.B $AUR_HELPER -Ss
.I pkg
.IP
.I Example - find packages related to a PDF viewer:
.RS
.nf
lazypac search pdf viewer
.fi
.RE
.IP
.I Example - search the AUR and sort results by vote count:
.RS
.nf
lazypac search spotify --sortby votes
.fi
.RE

.TP
.BI "info " "pkg"
Display detailed information about a package: version, description,
dependencies, install size, build date, and more.
Works for both installed and uninstalled packages.
Runs:
.B $AUR_HELPER -Si
.I pkg
.IP
.I Example - inspect a package before deciding to install it:
.RS
.nf
lazypac info neovim
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B list
Print the names of all installed packages without version numbers.
Useful for piping into other tools.
Runs:
.B $AUR_HELPER -Qq
.IP
.I Example - count how many packages are installed:
.RS
.nf
lazypac list | wc -l
.fi
.RE
.IP
.I Example - check whether a specific package name appears in the list:
.RS
.nf
lazypac list | grep python
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B installed
Print the names and versions of all installed packages.
Runs:
.B $AUR_HELPER -Q
.IP
.I Example - see what is installed and pipe it to a file for backup:
.RS
.nf
lazypac installed > ~/pkg-backup.txt
.fi
.RE
.IP
.I Example - find all installed packages whose name contains "lib":
.RS
.nf
lazypac installed | grep lib
.fi
.RE

.TP
.BI "check " "pkg [pkg ...]"
For each package listed, print
.I "pkg: installed"
or
.I "pkg: not installed"
on its own line.
Runs:
.B $AUR_HELPER -Q
.I pkg
for each argument.
.IP
.I Example - verify a single package before a script relies on it:
.RS
.nf
lazypac check git
.fi
.RE
.IP
.I Example - check several tools at once after a fresh install:
.RS
.nf
lazypac check git curl wget rsync
.fi
.RE

.TP
.BI "deps " "pkg"
Display the full dependency tree for a package, recursively expanding
all dependencies into a visual tree.
Requires
.BR pactree (8),
which ships with
.BR pacman-contrib .
Runs:
.B pactree
.I pkg
.IP
.I Example - understand what a package pulls in before installing it:
.RS
.nf
lazypac deps mesa
.fi
.RE
.IP
.I Example - show the reverse dependency tree (what depends on this package):
.RS
.nf
lazypac deps -r python
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B orphans
List packages that were installed as dependencies but are no longer
required by any other installed package.
Runs:
.B $AUR_HELPER -Qdt
.IP
.I Example - check for orphans after removing a large application:
.RS
.nf
lazypac orphans
.fi
.RE
.IP
.I Example - pipe the orphan list into a file to review before removing:
.RS
.nf
lazypac orphans > ~/orphans.txt
.fi
.RE

.SS Pacnew / pacsave

After a system upgrade, pacman may leave behind
.I .pacnew
files (new default configs, not applied to avoid overwriting your changes) or
.I .pacsave
files (backups of configs it would have overwritten).

.TP
.B pacnew
Search
.I /etc
recursively for any
.I .pacnew
or
.I .pacsave
files and list their paths.
If none are found, prints a confirmation message.
Runs:
.B find /etc \(rs( -name *.pacnew -o -name *.pacsave \(rs)
.IP
.I Example - check for leftover config files after an upgrade:
.RS
.nf
lazypac pacnew
# /etc/ssh/sshd_config.pacnew
# /etc/locale.gen.pacnew
.fi
.RE

.SS Logs

.TP
.B log
List all upgrade log files saved by
.BR safe-upgrade ,
showing file sizes and timestamps.
If no logs exist yet, prints a hint to run
.BR safe-upgrade .
Runs:
.B ls -lh $LOG_DIR
.IP
.I Example - see how many upgrades have been logged and how large each file is:
.RS
.nf
lazypac log
# -rw-r--r-- 1 ric ric 1.2K May 16 12:00 upgrade_20260516_120000.log
# -rw-r--r-- 1 ric ric 3.4K May 10 09:15 upgrade_20260510_091500.log
.fi
.RE

.TP
.BI "log " file
Open
.I file
from the log directory in
.BR less (1)
for reading.
.I file
must be a bare filename (not a path); use
.B lazypac log
first to see what is available.
If the file does not exist,
.B lazypac
prints an error and suggests listing available logs.
Runs:
.B less $LOG_DIR/file
.IP
.I Example - read the log from a specific upgrade:
.RS
.nf
lazypac log upgrade_20260516_120000.log
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B logclean
Delete all
.I *.log
files from the log directory and print how many were removed.
.IP
.I Example - free up space and start a fresh log history:
.RS
.nf
lazypac logclean
# Removing 5 log file(s) from /home/ric/.local/share/lazypac...
# Done.
.fi
.RE

.SS Cleanup

.TP
.B remove-orphans
Remove all orphan packages and their leftover config files.
If no orphans are found the command exits cleanly with a message instead
of passing an empty argument list to the AUR helper.
Runs:
.B $AUR_HELPER -Rns $($AUR_HELPER -Qdtq)
.IP
.I Example - clean up after removing a large application that pulled in many deps:
.RS
.nf
lazypac remove-orphans
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B cache-size
Print the total size and file count of the package cache at
.IR /var/cache/pacman/pkg/ .
Runs:
.B du -sh /var/cache/pacman/pkg/
.IP
.I Example - check how much disk the cache is using before cleaning:
.RS
.nf
lazypac cache-size
# Cache location : /var/cache/pacman/pkg/
# Total size     : 4.2G
# Cached files   : 1337
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B cache-clean
Remove cached package files for versions that are no longer current,
keeping the latest installed version cached (useful for quick downgrades).
Runs:
.B sudo pacman -Sc
.IP
.I Example - reclaim disk space after a large upgrade:
.RS
.nf
lazypac cache-clean
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B cache-clean-old
Remove all cached package files for packages that are no longer installed
on the system.
Requires
.BR paccache (8)
from
.BR pacman-contrib .
Runs:
.B sudo paccache -ruk0
.PP
For finer control (e.g. keep the last 2 versions of every installed package)
use
.B paccache
directly:
.RS
.nf
paccache -rk 2
.fi
.RE
.IP
.I Example - free space taken by packages you already removed:
.RS
.nf
lazypac cache-clean-old
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B cache-clean-all
Remove the entire package cache, including the currently installed versions.
Use with care - after this you cannot downgrade without re-downloading.
Runs:
.B sudo pacman -Scc
.IP
.I Example - wipe the cache completely on a low-disk-space system:
.RS
.nf
lazypac cache-clean-all
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B help
Print a formatted command reference table showing every command, its
description, and the underlying call with the detected AUR helper name.
.IP
.I Example:
.RS
.nf
lazypac help
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B version
Print the installed version of
.BR lazypac .
.IP
.I Example:
.RS
.nf
lazypac version
# lazypac 1.2.0
.fi
.RE

.SH FLAG PASSTHROUGH
Every argument that appears after the
.I command
(and after any package names) is forwarded verbatim to the underlying
tool.
This means any flag accepted by
.BR yay / paru / pacman
works transparently:

.PP
.RS
.nf
lazypac install firefox --noconfirm
    \(-> yay -S firefox --noconfirm

lazypac upgrade --devel
    \(-> yay -Syu --devel

lazypac safe-upgrade --devel
    \(-> yay -Syu --devel  (with before/after logging)

lazypac search linux --sortby votes
    \(-> yay -Ss linux --sortby votes
.fi
.RE

.SH MULTIPLE PACKAGES
All commands that accept a package name accept multiple package names.
They are all forwarded to the underlying tool in one call:

.PP
.RS
.nf
lazypac install firefox chromium vlc
    \(-> yay -S firefox chromium vlc

lazypac remove gimp inkscape
    \(-> yay -Rs gimp inkscape

lazypac check git curl wget rsync
    \(-> reports each package independently

lazypac purge gimp inkscape --noconfirm
    \(-> yay -Rns gimp inkscape --noconfirm
.fi
.RE

.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.local/share/lazypac/
Default log directory. Override by setting
.B XDG_DATA_HOME
before running lazypac.

.TP
.I ~/.local/share/lazypac/upgrade_TIMESTAMP.log
Per-upgrade log file produced by
.BR safe-upgrade .
Each file records the date, the AUR helper used, and a table of every
package whose version changed (old version \(-> new version) or that was
newly installed.

